# Command glow

## What does this command do:

Render Markdown in the terminal

## Installed from

For Fedora install using: `sudo dnf install glow`
For Raspberry Pi install using:
```
sudo mkdir -p /etc/apt/keyrings
curl -fsSL https://repo.charm.sh/apt/gpg.key | sudo gpg --dearmor -o /etc/apt/keyrings/charm.gpg
echo "deb [signed-by=/etc/apt/keyrings/charm.gpg] https://repo.charm.sh/apt/ * *" | sudo tee /etc/apt/sources.list.d/charm.list
sudo apt update
sudo apt install glow
```
For Mac install using: `homebrew install glow`

## Command path

For Fedora run: `glow`
For Raspberry Pi run: `glow`
For Mac run: `glow`

## Command documentation

Docs can be found at https://github.com/charmbracelet/glow

## Command options

# Render a markdown file
glow <file.md>

# Render markdown from a URL
glow <url>

# Open TUI mode (browse local markdown files)
glow --tui

# Show all system files and directories (TUI mode only)
glow --all

# Show line numbers (TUI mode only)
glow --line-numbers

# Display with pager
glow --pager <file.md>

# Set a style (name or JSON path)
glow --style <style> <file.md>

# Wrap at a specific width (0 to disable)
glow --width <N> <file.md>

# Preserve newlines in output
glow --preserve-new-lines <file.md>

# Use a custom config file
glow --config <path/to/config.yml> <file.md>

# Edit the glow config
glow config

# Print version
glow --version
